<DOC><DOCNO> AP891215-0158 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2031EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India     12-15 0433</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India,0448</SECOND><HEAD>Moslem Separatists Celebrating Hostage Swap Battle Police</HEAD><BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Moslem separatists celebrating therelease of five radicals in exchange for a government minister'skidnapped daughter hurled gasoline bombs at police Friday inclashes that killed five people.   Curfews were imposed in five towns of the northern state ofJammu-Kashmir after widespread violence and to stop Moslemseparatists from demonstrating after Wednesday's swap. Securityforces were told to shoot violators.   Officials said two people were killed and 30 others were injuredin Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir with a populationof 700,000. The Moslem-majority state lies on the Pakistan border.   Officers opened fired in the town of Anantnag when mobs hurledstones and gasoline bombs on police barricades, said Shoaib S. Ali,deputy inspector general of the state police.   In Shupiyan, crowds burned a forest office building and attackedpolice contingents. Police fatally shot three men and wounded 30others, said Divisional Commissioner Mohammad Shafi Pandit, asenior government official.   Curfews were imposed in Sopore and Baramullah on Thursday afterseparatist violence left two teen-agers dead and 50 others injured.   Security forces were ordered to shoot curfew violators Friday,Ali said. Soldiers have been posted in all five towns, he said.   Five militants of the Kashmir Liberation Front were releasedWednesday in exchange for the Rubaiya Sayeed, held hostage sinceher abduction by the separatist group Dec. 8.   Ms. Sayeed, 22, is a medical intern at a Srinagar hospital andthe youngest daughter of Home Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, aKashmiri and the first Moslem to be named to the sensitive postthat oversees police and internal security.   Prime Minister V.P. Singh said the release of the militants wasnot ``bowing to terrorists,'' but a decision that took into account``the overall situation.''   He said the new government, formed Dec. 2, will assess thesituation in the state but was not in favor of precipitate actionbecuase ``it is a delicate situation.''   The Kashmir Liberation Front, formed in 1965, wantsJammu-Kashmir to secede from India and become either independent ormerge with Islamic Pakistan.   Moslems make up 64 percent of Jammu-Kashmir's 5 million peoplebut only about 12 percent of the country's 880 million people.Hindus account for about 80 percent of the population.   Kashmir, the northwestern region of the state, is claimed byboth India and Pakistan, and the two countries have fought threewars over the territory since gaining independence from Britain in1947.   A cease-fire line monitored by the United Nations separates thestate into Indian and Pakistani territory.</TEXT></DOC>